<div id="review_2184517794" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2184517794" />
    <a title="Cris (the_book_adventurer)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/61034608-cris-the-book-adventurer"><img alt="Cris (the_book_adventurer)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1593217520p2/61034608.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2184517794?book_show_action=true">Nov 14, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cris (the_book_adventurer)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cris (the_book_adventurer)" href="/user/show/61034608-cris-the-book-adventurer">Cris (the_book_adventurer)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2184517794" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10933932314111698940">A Good Quote: &quot;Nothing had ever met my expectations, since nothing could compete with my doctoring imagination, my pathetic compulsion to make the world quainter, funner, kinder, and more mysterious than it actually was&quot; (Maupin, 242). <br/><br/>Armistead Maupin took an experience from his own life, fictionalized it, and offered the world an intriguing story about a young troubled boy who finds solace in the voice of a male radio-show host. The book begins with an in-depth view of both the young boy and t</span>
  <span id="freeText10933932314111698940" style="display:none">A Good Quote: "Nothing had ever met my expectations, since nothing could compete with my doctoring imagination, my pathetic compulsion to make the world quainter, funner, kinder, and more mysterious than it actually was" (Maupin, 242). <br /><br />Armistead Maupin took an experience from his own life, fictionalized it, and offered the world an intriguing story about a young troubled boy who finds solace in the voice of a male radio-show host. The book begins with an in-depth view of both the young boy and the male protagonist (the radio-show host), ultimately setting the scene for the actions that resulted in the young boy finding comfort through the radio. Starting from the very first chapter, the reader is hit with a variety of crucial events that have happened and are happening with the main characters, giving way for a powerful opening for Maupin's book. Throughout the story, the reader is continuously given bits and pieces of each character's life story, and we are allowed the opportunity to analyze for ourselves what exactly is going on and what could potentially happen. Despite what some reviews have said, this book is not particularly a mystery or a thriller; it is more of a fast-paced novel that has elements of a psychological thriller, a story that nestles in your mind and gets you thinking. Yet, because of how fast-paced the story is, and the aspects of thrill that have been incorporated using word choice, tone, and character development, I couldn't help but be immensely unsatisfied with how it was all brought to a close. As I was reading, I was going through theory after theory right alongside Jess, Gabriel, Ashe, and even Anna. The whole time I'm thinking, "What is going on? I NEED TO KNOW!!" Unfortunately, I think my brain got caught up in all the theories that were flying from each character, which resulted in the ending being insufficient for what I was expecting. The plot of this true-story-turned-fiction was brilliant, and I think it would have made for a great thriller had the theories of a few of the characters been justified. In itself, it is a worthwhile read, and I would also recommend reviewing Maupin's true experience, as it provides suggestive background material for The Night Listener! Overall, 3 Stars!!! </span>
  <a data-text-id="10933932314111698940" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


