  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/415044939?book_show_action=true">Sep 15, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sarah Cypher" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sarah Cypher" href="/user/show/4673485-sarah-cypher">Sarah Cypher</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer415044939" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2367158822981975925">I admit it: I&apos;ve come late to Armistead Maupin. I&apos;ve never read <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16255.Tales_of_the_City__Tales_of_the_City___1_' title='Tales of the City (Tales of the City, #1) by Armistead Maupin' rel='nofollow noopener'>Tales of the City</a>, nor his short stories. It&apos;s always an uncertain endeavor, beginning to read an author by picking up one of his most postmodern, meta-fictional novels. But give me 1,738.4 miles of highway and the wide-open Mojave Desert to cross, and y&apos;know, I&apos;ll read just about anything.<br/><br/>Imagine how lucky I felt, then, when <i>The Night Listener</i> engaged me so much that I soldiered through it despite my signature bouts of motion sickn</span>
  <span id="freeText2367158822981975925" style="display:none">I admit it: I've come late to Armistead Maupin. I've never read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/16255.Tales_of_the_City__Tales_of_the_City___1_" title="Tales of the City (Tales of the City, #1) by Armistead Maupin" rel="nofollow noopener">Tales of the City</a>, nor his short stories. It's always an uncertain endeavor, beginning to read an author by picking up one of his most postmodern, meta-fictional novels. But give me 1,738.4 miles of highway and the wide-open Mojave Desert to cross, and y'know, I'll read just about anything.<br /><br />Imagine how lucky I felt, then, when <i>The Night Listener</i> engaged me so much that I soldiered through it despite my signature bouts of motion sickness. Had I started with any of the other books in my vacation reading pile, I probably would have spent most of that road trip reading bumper stickers and queasily watching the mesas for signs of life. Granted, the print was bigger in <i>The Night Listener</i>, but Maupin is <i>funny</i>. He also writes credibly about the fissures of a broken heart, and the durability of a love that has been put through a wringer by marriage.<br /><br />I knew almost nothing about the story when I picked up the novel, and found it to be a literary novel tightened and paced by the trappings of a mystery. There is no crime to solve at the core of this mystery, but (and I'm avoiding a spoiler here), suffice to say Maupin finds a fresh, affecting one that turns <i>The Night Listener</i> into a page-turner.<br /><br />It's not a life-changing book--it leaves the reader with a few questions, as there is certainly enough ambiguity in its quasi-resolution to make it a good conversation-piece with friends. If you only have a little bit of time for fiction and you're determined to make it through the canon of Western literature, you probably want to chew on something a little meatier; but I'd call this one a satisfying summer read for people who don't abide fluff.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2367158822981975925" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


