  <span id="freeText12643642161716740603" style="display:none">I didnâ€™t enjoy this book as much as I enjoyed Maupinâ€™s Tales of the City series. I loved them â€“ but that WAS quite a few years ago, maybe Iâ€™m just older and more cynical but this felt more manipulative than his earlier work. I always loved his easy style and intimate confessional tone, and that was all still there and still very enjoyable. But it all seemed a little weary and the confessions trotted out as if to order rather than offered with an open heart. The ending was also kind of unresolved. Iâ€™m not a reader who wants everything tied up with a bow all the time but in this case I felt it needed a little more certainty, a more definite resolution, which I think his style leads the reader to expect. It felt as though the narrative was pushing and pulling me along in definite directions but wasnâ€™t clear about why. I did love the ease with which Maupin weaves different threads together â€“ the main storyline of his involvement with a, possibly fictional, child author and his own relationship difficulties and unresolved issues with his father. As a meditation on the child/parent relationship, I thought it was perceptive and touching. So, a good read, entertaining and thought provoking but I wouldnâ€™t say it was this authorâ€™s best work. </span>
