<span id="freeTextContainer2285952175049802077">I actually liked the movie much better than the book. It was creepier and weirder, whereas the book was rather annoying. This is a fictionalized account of something real that happened to the author, but Maupin emphasized more his relationship with his ex-boyfriend and his father. I found him to be very whiny and annoying. The book also had what I consider a &quot;trick&quot; ending in which I felt duped and deceived, and irritated. The writing is okay, but I wouldn&apos;t recommend the book. See the movie ins</span>
  <span id="freeText2285952175049802077" style="display:none">I actually liked the movie much better than the book. It was creepier and weirder, whereas the book was rather annoying. This is a fictionalized account of something real that happened to the author, but Maupin emphasized more his relationship with his ex-boyfriend and his father. I found him to be very whiny and annoying. The book also had what I consider a "trick" ending in which I felt duped and deceived, and irritated. The writing is okay, but I wouldn't recommend the book. See the movie instead. Not sure if it has the same title, but it stars Robin Williams as Maupin. It's so much better than the book. </span>
